sndlib.core.statistics
Enum ProblemStatisticValueKeys

java.lang.Object
  java.lang.Enum<ProblemStatisticValueKeys>
      sndlib.core.statistics.ProblemStatisticValueKeys
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<ProblemStatisticValueKeys>, ProblemStatisticValueKey
public enum ProblemStatisticValueKeys
extends java.lang.Enum<ProblemStatisticValueKeys>
implements ProblemStatisticValueKey

This enumeration implements all currently defined statistical values of a network design Problem.

For a given problem a single statistical value can be calculated by invoking the calculateValue(Problem) method of the corresponding enumeration constant. To compute, e.g., the average node out-degree of a given problem, write this line:

   ProblemStatisticValueKeys.NODE_AVG_OUT_DEGREE.calculateValue(problem)


To calculate the entire statistics of a given problem make use of the static factory methods of ProblemStatistics, like

   ProblemStatistics.newStatistics(problem)

Author:
Roman Klaehne
See Also:
ProblemStatistics

NODE_MIN_IN_DEGREE

public static final ProblemStatisticValueKeys NODE_MIN_IN_DEGREE
Calculates the minimum in-degree over all nodes.

For a directed link model the in-degree of a node is defined as the number of its incident links of which that node is the target. Otherwise there is no definite target node and thus the in-degree is simply the number of its incident links.

LINK_DENSITY

public static final ProblemStatisticValueKeys LINK_DENSITY
Calculates the link density.

The link density is the ratio between the number of non-parallel links in the network and the number of links in the corresponding complete network (which is (n * (n - 1)) / 2, where n denotes the number of nodes).

DEMAND_DENSITY

public static final ProblemStatisticValueKeys DEMAND_DENSITY
Calculates the demand density.

The demand density is the ratio between the number of non-parallel demands and the maximal possible number of demands in the network. (which is (n * (n - 1)) / 2, where n denotes the number of nodes).

If a demand provides a routing unit different from one then its demand value is multiplied by its routing unit.

DEMAND_EXPL_PATHS_TOTAL_HOP_LENGTH

public static final ProblemStatisticValueKeys DEMAND_EXPL_PATHS_TOTAL_HOP_LENGTH
Calculates the sum of the lengths of all demand's admissible paths, where the length of a path is the number of links it contains (hop-length). If no demand specifies any admissible paths then this statistic value is evaluated to zero.

DEMAND_EXPL_PATHS_TOTAL_KMS_LENGTH

public static final ProblemStatisticValueKeys DEMAND_EXPL_PATHS_TOTAL_KMS_LENGTH
Calculates the sum of the lengths of all demand's admissible paths, where the length of a path is calculated in kilometer.

To get a meaningful result it is assumed that the nodes in the network have coordinates which can be interpreted in a geographical manner.

If no demand specifies any admissible paths then this statistic value is evaluated to zero.
